#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:1
msgid "Raw identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.30](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.30-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust, like many programming languages, has the concept of \"keywords\". "
"These identifiers mean something to the language, and so you cannot use them "
"in places like variable names, function names, and other places. Raw "
"identifiers let you use keywords where they would not normally be allowed."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:10
msgid "For example, `match` is a keyword. If you try to compile this function:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:18
msgid "You'll get this error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:28
msgid "You can write this with a raw identifier:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:36
msgid "\"foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:36
msgid "\"foobar\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:40
msgid "Note the `r#` prefix on both the function name as well as the call."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:42
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:44
msgid ""
"This feature is useful for a few reasons, but the primary motivation was "
"inter-edition situations. For example, `try` is not a keyword in the 2015 "
"edition, but is in the 2018 edition. So if you have a library that is "
"written in Rust 2015 and has a `try` function, to call it in Rust 2018, "
"you'll need to use the raw identifier."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:50
msgid "New keywords"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:52
msgid "The new confirmed keywords in edition 2018 are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:54
msgid "`async` and `await`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:58
msgid ""
"Here, `async` is reserved for use in `async fn` as well as in `async ||` "
"closures and `async { .. }` blocks. Meanwhile, `await` is reserved to keep "
"our options open with respect to `await!(expr)` syntax. See [RFC 2394]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2394-async_await."
"md#final-syntax-for-the-await-expression) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:62
msgid "`try`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/raw-identifiers.md:66
msgid ""
"The `do catch { .. }` blocks have been renamed to `try { .. }` and to "
"support that, the keyword `try` is reserved in edition 2018. See [RFC 2388]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/2388) for more details."
msgstr ""
